    {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::naming_quality::legacy_google_terms_in_provider_neutral_identity",
      "confidence": "high",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "summary": "Google-specific names still label provider-neutral identity data across core auth APIs",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "naming_quality",
        "related_files": [
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/model/User.java",
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/repository/UserRepository.java",
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/service/UserService.java",
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/service/JwtTokenService.java",
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/service/AuthenticatedUserIdentity.java",
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/service/NormalizedIdentity.java"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "`UserService.legacyGoogleCompatibilityId(...)` writes non-Google identities into `User.googleId`, so the field name no longer matches the value it carries.",
          "`UserRepository.findByGoogleId(...)` and `JwtTokenService.generateToken(String email, String googleId)` extend that Google-only term into repository and JWT APIs that now participate in a multi-provider identity model.",
          "`AuthenticatedUserIdentity` still exposes `legacyGoogleId`, even though that path represents the old contract shape rather than a reliably Google-only concept."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Rename the compatibility-facing identifiers to provider-neutral terms such as `legacyIdentityKey` or `legacyProviderUserId` across the entity/service/JWT/repository APIs, and keep any truly Google-specific naming only at explicit backward-compatibility boundaries like the persisted column or legacy token claim.",
        "reasoning": "",
        "summary_hash": "f8d45021"
      },
      "status": "open",
      "kind": "issue",
      "primary_command": "desloppify plan resolve \"review::.::holistic::naming_quality::legacy_google_terms_in_provider_neutral_identity\" --note \"<what you did>\" --confirm",
      "queue_position": 6,
      "plan_cluster": {
        "name": "naming-fixes",
        "description": "Rename for clarity",
        "total_items": 3,
        "action_steps": [
          {
            "title": "Rename legacyGoogleId in AuthenticatedUserIdentity",
            "effort": "trivial"
          },
          {
            "title": "Rename loginMethod field to match its purpose",
            "effort": "small"
          },
          {
            "title": "Clarify Microsoft isConfigured naming",
            "effort": "trivial"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::naming_quality::login_method_label_actually_stores_flow",
      "confidence": "high",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "summary": "`loginMethod` is named like an auth method but stores client/server flow values",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "naming_quality",
        "related_files": [
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/model/AuthFlow.java",
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/model/User.java",
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/service/UserService.java",
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/controller/dto/UserResponse.java"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "`UserService.applyProviderIdentityFields(...)` stores `identity.loginFlow().name()` via `user.setLoginMethod(...)`, so values like `SERVER_SIDE` and `CLIENT_SIDE` are written into a field called method.",
          "`AuthFlow.fromLoginMethod(...)` converts that same persisted value back into `AuthFlow`, confirming the data represents flow/channel semantics rather than an authentication method or provider.",
          "`UserResponse` exposes both `loginMethod` and `lastLoginFlow`, which makes it easy for readers to assume they are separate concepts when they are really overlapping flow terminology."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Rename the internal field/accessors to `loginFlow` or `authFlow`, or if the external/persisted label must remain for compatibility, isolate the legacy `loginMethod` name at the serialization boundary and use flow-specific names in the core model and service APIs.",
        "reasoning": "",
        "summary_hash": "270e26cd"
      },
      "status": "open",
      "kind": "issue",
